I noticed that the Field method of the Mutation class is not propagating the keywords arguments that
are passed to it. 
```
class Mutation(ObjectType):
    ...

    @classmethod
    def Field(cls, *args, **kwargs):
        return Field(
            cls._meta.output, args=cls._meta.arguments, resolver=cls._meta.resolver
        )
```
This caused me some problems when I wanted to fully document my API and I wasn't
able to set the description of the fields correctly.

Hello, I was trying to customise the output of a SerializerMutation in order to have it nested[1]

For now I made a custom SerializerMutation that accepts a `return_output_fields` that when it is False it will not return any output fields other than the errors.

@syrusakbary @spockNinja what do you think? I can send a PR with this change 

```python
class CreateCompany(SerializerMutation):
    company = graphene.Field(CompanyType)

    class Meta:
        serializer_class = CompanySerializer
        return_output_fields = False

    @classmethod
    def perform_mutate(cls, serializer, info):
        obj = serializer.save()

        return CreateCompany(company=obj)
```

[1] I'm doing this because I want to reuse the same Type for a query and a Mutation, so that I can leverage the client cache better :)

I'm trying to run `fasttext` command in `node.js` using `child_process.spawn`.
I'm executing it in interactive mode (passing the `-` option), so that can get the `stdin` to take input from the console and output results to `stdout`. I'm using this mode, to send commands to the child via the `child.stdin.write( data+'\r\n' );`. I suppose to get all the results (i.e. the predictions) in the callback `child.stdout.on('data')`, but it seems I'm not getting all data wrote by `fasttext` in the `stdout`.

My `JavaScript` code looks like:

```javascript
        var exec = function(name,command,params,options,callback) {
         
        var _options = {
            // Prepare child to run independently of its parent process
            //detached: true
        };
        for (var attrname in options) { _options[attrname] = options[attrname]; }
    
        var created_time= ( new Date() ).toISOString();
        var task = require('child_process').spawn(command, params, _options);
        task.stdout.on('data', function(result) {
            var out=new Buffer(result,'utf-8').toString();
            callback(out);
        });
        task.on('error', function(error) {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.error("exec:%s pid:%d error:\n%@",name,task.pid,error);
        });
        task.on('uncaughtException', function (error) {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.error("exec:%s pid:%s uncaughtException:\n%@",name,task.pid,error);
        });
        task.stdout.on('end', function(data) {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.debug("exec:%s end.",name);
        });
        task.stderr.on('data', function(data) {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.debug("exec:%s stderr:%s",name,data);
        });
        task.on('close', (code, signal) => {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.warn('task:%s pid:%s terminated due to receipt of signal:%s',name,task.pid,signal);
        });
        task.on('exit', function(code) {
            if(self.logger) self.logger.debug("exec:%s exit.",name);
            if (code != 0) {
                var error=new Error();
                error.description= command + ' ' + params.join(' ');
                error.code=code;
                if(self.logger) self.logger.error("exec:%s pid:%d error:\n%@",name,task.pid,error);
            }
            // at exit explicitly kill exited task
            task.kill('SIGINT');
        });
        return task;
    }//exec

    // fork a child
    var load = function(model,callback) {
        var m=exec('fasttext','./fasttext', ['predict', model, '-'], {}, callback);
        m.stdout.pipe(process.stdout);
        return m;
    }//load
    
    // send data to child task
    var send = function(task,data) {
        task.stdin.setEncoding('utf-8');
        task.stdin.write( data );
        task.stdin.write('\r\n');
    }//send
```

From the `node` parent process I run the command like

```javascript
    var model=load(modelFile,
    function(prediction) {
        console.log(prediction);
    });
    send(model,datum);
```

Looking at the [code][1] `fasttext` writes a line with `std::cout << " " << data;` and ends the stream with `std::cout << std::endl;.`, so I would expect in the parent node process the get the `end` and `data` events as usual on the`stdout`, but this seems to do not have the expected behavior.

Any suggestion?
 
  [1]: https://github.com/facebookresearch/fastText/blob/a9d7c2c6393ccca7276df0699441509fe95367e5/src/fasttext.cc#L337

Pybind11 fails to compile with newer MSVC compilers, under /permissive- mode (extra standards conformance). Disabling the new two-phase lookup (with /Zc:twoPhase-) fixes the issue, but it ought to be able to compile without it. 

`#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
using namespace pybind11;

double Mult(double a, double b) { return a*b; }


void export_Mult(pybind11::module& m) {
      m.def("mult", &Mult);
}`

produces:
`pybind11\cast.h(1416): error C2187: syntax error: ')' was unexpected here`

Hi! I noticed that attempts to call bind'ed base class functions without binding the base class lead to an error. Its looks like Python expecting the base-type object instead of descendent one (see error log below). I guess this could be 'fixed' by binding lambda functions for such cases but it would be nice if that would not be necessary.

Thanks,

```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

class Base
{
public:
	void foo_base() {}
};

class C : public Base
{
public:
	void foo_c() {}
};
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");

	pybind11::class_<C> cl(m, "C");
	cl.def(pybind11::init<>());

	cl.def("foo_c", &C::foo_c);
	cl.def("foo_base", &C::foo_base);

    return m.ptr();
}
```


ipython log:
```
In [1]: c = C()
In [2]: c.foo_base()

TypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-2-9bea0f40fb1f> in <module>()
----> 1 c.foo_base()

TypeError: Incompatible function arguments. The following argument types are supported:
    1. (Base) -> NoneType
```

@oberstet: Is testing for code coverage something we'd want to complement our efforts towards CI?

I doubt it really pays of for a small project, but I'm looking into the topic for the first time and I'm curious enough to spend a bit time on it.

On first look it could definitely help to improve our unittests (a quick investigation with `coverage` revealed some blind spots)...

Every time a layer is created on the frontend (for instance, with a DrawControl) and added to the Map, we don't know about it on the Python side, and we don't create an equivalent python model for those layers. We should be able to fix this synchronization issue by using the `layeradd` event on Leaflet Map object:

```javascript
// Inside the LeafletMapView class
this.obj.on('layeradd', function(event) {
    var added_layer = event.layer;
    // Create a new model on the Javascript and Python side, if it doesn't exist yet
});
```

